<TITLE> Law Commission lay inoperative in last 7 years: new chief </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 30 (bdnews24.com)The Law Commission was not operational for the last seven years, it new chairman Abdur Rashid said Thursday. "People have forgotten the importance of law over the last seven years. The successive governments were unable to perceive the effectiveness of law," Rashid said at the publication of a research report on information of death from accident at work place at the National Press Club. He refereed to the rules by the 2001-2006 BNP-led coalition government and 2007-2008 caretaker administration. "In democracy, the necessity of law commission is widely known to all. But its importance was not highlighted before the nation earlier." The former High Court judge was appointed on Apr 20. Justice Abdur Rashid succeeded chairman ex-justice Mostafa Kamal who ended his three-year tenure on Dec 5, 2007. On April 15, law minister Shafiq Ahmed confirmed his appointment to the reporters and said, "If effectively run, Law Commission will ensure public welfare through updating many laws." The law commission came into being in 1996 when the previous Awami League government formulated law commission act. The commission act stipulates that a retired chief justice should helm the commission as chairman with two ex-judges as members. The commission started its journey with chairman, members and 34 officials and employees in line with the commission act. Initially the commission enjoyed much importance giving opinion over formation, cancellation and reform of law. bd
